{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e3d28937-7b1b-4b46-9a7f-9f89067826ac","content":"In .NET MAUI, the app lifecycle moved to the `Window` class. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to window lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window Event |\n|---------------|-------------------|\n| `OnStart` | `Created` |\n| `OnSleep` | `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume` | `Resumed` |\n\nThere's also `Activated`, `Deactivated`, and `Destroying` for more granular control. Alternatively, you can use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` for platform-specific lifecycle hooks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"267c9d32-261c-47bb-ab78-4f5b0a360db5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. Instead of overriding those methods directly, you use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. Specifically:\n\n1. You can override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to window events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, `Destroying`.\n\n\n2. Alternatively, you can configure platform-specific lifecycle events through `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.\n\nThe mapping is fairly direct: `OnStart` maps to `Window.Created`, `OnSleep` corresponds to either `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped`, and `OnResume` aligns with `Window.Resumed` or `Window.Activated`. The key difference is that the `Application` class still exists in MAUI, but the actual lifecycle management now flows through the `Window` class, which you typically override in `CreateWindow()`.\n\nThe window lifecycle events available are `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, and `Destroying`, so the cleaner mapping is `OnStart` → `Window.Created`, `OnSleep` → `Window.Stopped`, and `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed`.","outputTokens":771,"requestId":"6C1A:30221B:7ECB24:878067:6A0AF646"},"id":"b9a13628-bbe6-410f-a9e7-44e17196f5ac","timestamp":"2026-05-18T11:21:56.724Z","parentId":"cd56cea8-c3ac-49c3-a738-20f4996990d4"}
